8-1- Introduction

A satellite's spatial resolution or field of view is dictated by orbital altitude, wavelength, and antenna size. Among the majority of radiometers flown today, the FOV ranges between 5 km at 100 GHz to 40 km at L-band radiometer at 1.4 GHz. Most atmospheric features change at a scale of tens of kilometers. Thus channels above 19 GHz and higher are suitable for atmospheric remote sensing. Land parameters vary from tens of meters to tens of kilometers - depending on the variable of interest. Thus, passive radiometry has some limitations in remote sensing of small-scale features of land surfaces. Remote sensing of land surface characteristics is by far more challenging than atmospheric and ocean variables because of its spatial heterogeneity.

8-2-2 Values for single scattering Albedo

Several investigators generated estimates of the single-scattering albedo a by fitting the model to experimental observations of the emission from vegetation canopies. The general consensus is that at 1.4 GHz, a varies over the range between 0.03 and 0.15, depending on vegetation type and structure. Even though for a given canopy structure the albedo a may have different values for h and v polarizations, the difference is small.
